- Typechecking uses `tsgo` (Go-based TS compiler); do not add cross-project `references` arrays to `tsconfig.json` (causes TS6305); `tsgo --incremental` writes `out-tsc/` directories with `.tsbuildinfo` even under `--noEmit`, and emitted stale `.js` files can be picked up by vitest's default test discovery — exclude `out-tsc/**` from vitest config (these dirs are gitignored stale build output, safe to delete); avoid `using`/`await using` in shipped code — Rolldown won't downlevel and Safari lacks support; use try/finally with `[Symbol.asyncDispose]()` instead. Node-runtime config files at the app root that are loaded outside the bundler (e.g. `apps/ui/react-router.config.ts` consumed by `@nx/react/router-plugin` and the netlify build via `pnpm nx build ui`) need both runtimes happy: at runtime they execute via `NX_PREFER_NODE_STRIP_TYPES=true` so `await import('./app/lib/static-paths.ts')` works (omitting the `.ts` suffix produces "Cannot find module ..." in netlify CI because Node's strip-types loader requires the explicit extension), but the same `.ts` suffix violates `tsgo`'s default `allowImportingTsExtensions=false` and fails `nx typecheck ui` with TS5097 — resolve by hoisting `react-router.config.ts` (and peer Node-runtime configs) out of `tsconfig.app.json`/`tsconfig.spec.json` into a dedicated `tsconfig.node.json` that enables `allowImportingTsExtensions`, so the netlify-required `.ts` extension stays explicit AND typecheck passes.
